SIMPLE: eminence
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Eminence
<hw>Em"i*nence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>eminentia</ets>, fr. <ets>eminens</ets> eminent: cf. F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧minence</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is
eminent or lofty; a high ground or place; a height.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Without either <qex>eminences</qex> or cavities.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The temple of honor ought to be seated on an
<qex>eminence</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An elevated condition among men; a place or station
above men in general, either in rank, office, or celebrity; social or
moral loftiness; high rank; distinction; preferment.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You 've too a woman's heart, which ever yet⟦br⟧
Affected <qex>eminence</qex>, wealth, sovereignty.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A title of honor, especially applied to a cardinal
in the Roman Catholic Church.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Eminency</ent>⟦br⟧
